</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Broad Bonds Classified as Nonperforming: The reclassification of $92 million in 
bonds in its investment portfolio in second quarter 1990 showed up in a report 
filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission. 
</P>
<P>
It marked the first time the Los Angeles financial services company has had to 
make such a classification. Jana Greer, a spokeswoman, said Broad had set aside 
$22 million to cover permanent losses. She added that the company expected the 
bonds to recover the $70 million in value not covered by the reserve fund and 
that the temporary loss would not have a material impact on Broad's 
$7.1-billion investment portfolio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
