<TEXT>
<P>
U.S. Deal Making Abroad Falls: Japanese, Swedish, Swiss and other foreign 
corporations have stepped up their global mergers and acquisitions activity, 
while American firms' deal making abroad has dropped off, the New York 
consulting firm KPMG Peat Marwick reported. American companies in the first 
half of 1990 made acquisitions valued at $8.1 billion, down from $11.4 billion 
in the year-ago period. Meanwhile, foreign purchases of U.S. companies rose to 
$27.9 billion from $23.9 billion. 
</P>
